# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: demographics-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] A nationwide census, commonly known as **Census 1991**, was conducted in the United Kingdom on Sunday 21 April 1991.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] The 1991 census was the first UK census to have a question on ethnic group.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] In the 1991 UK census 94.65% of people reported themselves as being White British, White Irish or White Other with 5.35% of people reporting themselves as coming from other minority groups.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] Other new questions were on limiting long-term illness and term-time address for students.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] A question about central heating replaced the previously used question on outside toilets.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] The census was also noted for a significant undercount of the population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] Despite being compulsory, a total of 572,000 people failed to respond to both the census form and follow-up interviews, 220,000 of them being males aged 20 to 29.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] It has been suggested that part of the lack of response could be due to people attempting to avoid registration for the poll tax.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/1991-united-kingdom-census] A total of 342 people were prosecuted for not completing their census returns.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A nationwide census, known as **Census 2001**, was conducted in the United Kingdom on Sunday, 29 April 2001.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was the 20th UK census and recorded a resident population of 58,789,194.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The 2001 UK census was organised by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Detailed results by region, council area, ward and output area are available from their respective websites.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Similar to previous UK censuses, the 2001 census was organised by the three statistical agencies, ONS, GROS, and NISRA, and coordinated at the national level by the Office for National Statistics.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Orders in Council to conduct the census, specifying the people and information to be included in the census, were made under the authority of the Census Act 1920 in Great Britain, and the Census Act (Northern Ireland) 1969 in Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales these regulations were made by the Census Order 2000 (SI 744/2000), in Scotland by the Census (Scotland) Order 2000 (SSI 68/2000), and in Northern Ireland by the Census Order (Northern Ireland) 2000 (SRNI 168/2000).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was administered through self-completion forms, in most cases delivered by enumerators to households and communal establishments in the three weeks before census night on 29 April.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time return by post was used as the main collection method, with enumerators following up in person where the forms were not returned.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The postal response rate was 88% in England and Wales, 91% in Scotland, and 92% in Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] A total of 81,000 field staff were employed across the UK (70,000 in England and Wales, 8,000 in Scotland and 3,000 in Northern Ireland).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was conducted at the height of the foot-and-mouth crisis, which led to extra precautions being adopted by the field staff, and suggestions that the census may have to be postponed.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, it was reported that the disease outbreak did not affect the effectiveness of the collection process.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was estimated to cost £259m over its 13-year cycle from the start of planning in 1993 to the delivery of final results in 2006.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Printing of the 30 million census forms was subcontracted to Polestar Group, and processing of the returned census forms was subcontracted to Lockheed Martin in a contract worth £54m.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were initially scanned into digital format, then read with OMR and OCR, with manual entry where the automatic process could not read the forms.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were then pulped and recycled, and the digital copies printed onto microfilm for storage and release after 100 years.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Once the data were returned to the statistics agencies it underwent further processing to ensure consistency and to impute missing values.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The overall response rate for the census, that is the proportion of the population who were included on a census form, was estimated to be 94% in England and Wales, 96.1% in Scotland and 95.2% in Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was due to a number of factors: households with no response, households excluding residents from their returns, and addresses not included in the enumeration.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In Manchester for example 25,000 people from 14,000 addresses were not enumerated because the address database was two years out of date.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Local Authority with the lowest response was Kensington and Chelsea with 64%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Hackney had the next lowest response at 72%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Out of all local authorities, the ten lowest response rates were all in London.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results still represent 100 per cent of the population, however, because some individuals not completing their forms were instead identified by census enumerators, and through the use of cross-matching with a follow-up survey.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results from the 2001 census were produced using a methodology known as the One Number Census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was an attempt to adjust the census counts and impute answers to allow for estimated under-enumeration measured by the Census Coverage Survey (sample size 320,000 households), resulting in a single set of population estimates.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Although the 1851 census had included a question about religion on a separate response sheet, whose completion was not compulsory, the 2001 census was the first in Great Britain to ask about the religion of respondents on the main census form.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] An amendment to the 1920 Census Act (the Census (Amendment) Act 2000) was passed by Parliament to allow the question to be asked, and to allow the response to this question to be optional.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] The inclusion of the question enabled the Jedi census phenomenon to take place in the United Kingdom.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales 390,127 people stated their religion as Jedi, as did 14,052 people in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 15% declared themselves of no religion (including Jedi at 0.7%, more than those who declared themselves as Sikh, Jewish or Buddhist) and 8% did not respond to the question.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Since the UK census relies on self-completion, the composition of the other ethnic group category is not fixed.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Analysis by the Office for National Statistics of the 220,000 people in England and Wales who ticked the other ethnic group box in the 2001 census reveals that 53 per cent were born in the Far East, 10 per cent in the UK, 10 per cent in the Middle East, and 7 per cent in Africa.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] People could write in an ethnic group under the 'other' heading.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] 26 per cent did not specify an ethnicity, but of the remainder 23 per cent wrote Filipino, 21 per cent Japanese, 11 per cent Vietnamese, 11 per cent Arab, 6 per cent Middle Eastern and 4 per cent North African.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic groups began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for English respondents.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of an English tick-box, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, if 'English' was written in under the "any other white background" it was not clear whether it would be counted as an ethnic group in same the way as the Welsh.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Following criticism, English was included as a tick-box option in the 2011 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] It is sometimes claimed that the 2001 census revealed that two-thirds of the population of Wales described themselves as of Welsh nationality.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] In fact, the 2001 census did not collect any information on nationality.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic group began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for Welsh respondents.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Prior to the census, *Plaid Cymru* backed a petition calling for the inclusion of a Welsh tickbox and for the National Assembly for Wales to have primary law-making powers and its own National Statistics Office.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of a Welsh tickbox, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time in a UK census, those wishing to describe their ethnicity as Cornish were given their own code number (06) on the 2001 UK census form, alongside those for people wishing to describe themselves as English, Welsh, Irish or Scottish.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] About 34,000 people in Cornwall and 3,500 people in the rest of the UK wrote on their census forms in 2001 that they considered their ethnic group to be Cornish.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] This represented nearly 7% of the population of Cornwall.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2001-united-kingdom-census] Various Cornish organisations were campaigning for the inclusion of the Cornish tick box on the next census in 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The **2021–2022 United Kingdom censuses** collectively comprised the 23rd census of the United Kingdom.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses of England and Wales, and Northern Ireland took place on 21 March 2021, and the census of Scotland took place later on 20 March 2022.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses were administered by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) in Northern Ireland, and by the National Records of Scotland in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] These were the first UK censuses for which most of the data was gathered online.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Two of the censuses went ahead despite the COVID-19 pandemic, in part because the information obtained would assist government and public understanding of the pandemic's impact.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census in Scotland was postponed, and took place in 2022.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses in 2021 and 2022 follow on from Beyond 2011, a project by the UK Statistics Authority to assess the value, cost, and alternatives to running a census in England and Wales in 2021.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The project recommended an England and Wales census be held in 2021, and that it be conducted predominantly by means of online returns.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results for England and Wales were released on 28 June 2022, while initial results for Scotland were released on 14 September 2023.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] After the 2011 census, both the UK coalition government and the main opposition party, Labour, expressed concerns about the rising costs of the decadal census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were also concerns about the value of continuing with the traditional approach adopted for the 2011 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This included whether collection methods were still fit for purpose in a rapidly changing society and whether census outputs, based on a survey conducted every ten years, would continue to meet the increasingly demanding needs of public and private sector users.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Emerging technological developments were seen as providing alternative and improved data gathering opportunities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] These concerns and opportunities led the UK Government to question if a supplementary or wholly alternative approach to the traditional 10-yearly census was required; more frequent, possibly annual, small-scale surveys could be employed instead.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2011, The Beyond 2011 Programme was established to look at alternatives to the traditional census approach.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority coordinated the project which was also undertaken by its counterparts in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Existing census gathering methods would be used only as an alternative, where online methods are not feasible.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A parallel announcement for Scotland's 2021 census was made by the National Records for Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS Director, Population and Demography Statistics was reported as saying that an estimated 60–65% of household returns would be completed online.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2014, the British House of Commons Public Accounts Committee (PAC) concluded in its report *Too soon to scrap the Census*, that the 2021 census should go ahead.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] It had reservations over the lack of investigation into the options for using administrative data and encouraged the UK Government to reassure the public about privacy concerns.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Minister for the Cabinet Office welcomed the recommendations for a predominantly online 2021 census for England and Wales supplemented by the use of governmental and other administrative data in a letter to the National Statistician in July 2014.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Under the Census Act 1920, it is for the United Kingdom Government and Parliament to determine the arrangements for census-taking in England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Parallel legislative procedures will be required in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] It would be late 2015 at the earliest before regulations were made.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Subject to this legislation being passed the census would be conducted on the same day in England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland to ensure coherence and consistency.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There is a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] As at 21 March 2021 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, the Census (Amendment) (Scotland) Act 2019 made provisions for voluntary questions about transgender status and sexual orientation to be asked.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Census (Return Particulars and Removal of Penalties) Act 2019 makes the same provision for England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The sexual orientation question would also be asked in Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The campaign 'If you're not religious, say so!' by Humanists UK aimed to change the wording of the census question on religion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This campaign encouraged non-religious people to tick 'no religion' in order to create a more accurate portrayal of religiousness in the UK.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Another campaign by the Climate Census campaign group suggested writing in 'Climate concerned' in response to the religion question, to demand climate action from the government.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics published an online guidance titled *What is your Sex* for the 2021 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance provided that a respondent should answer according to official documents such as their passport.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Self-identification is already recognised in some countries.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A gender marker on a British passport can be changed in a less formal procedure than acquiring a legally enforceable gender recognition certificate.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In March 2021, Fair Play for Women, an anti-transgender campaign group against self-identification, applied for judicial review in England and Wales and argued that such incidental self-identification should not be allowed in census-taking.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In the absence of opposition or intervention from any interested party, the judge ordered an interim revision of the guidance.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The government conceded and accepted the order.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS withdrew from the High Court proceedings.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Some academics criticised what they said was the ONS's confusion between the concepts of sex and gender identity.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Other academics supported the design of the census questions, for example, on the ground that the transgender population is very small.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, similar pieces of guidance have been published since the previous census in 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Parliament also sought to amend the census Act in 2019 to clarify the meaning of sex in that legislation to include gender identity.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The plan was abandoned and changes were instead made in subordinate legislation.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In August 2021, National Records of Scotland issued guidelines regarding the sex question in the 2022 Scottish census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance states that "If you are transgender the answer you give can be different from what is on your birth certificate.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] You do not need a Gender Recognition Certificate (GRC)".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority wrote to National Records of Scotland to question the guidelines.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In December 2021, Fair Play for Women applied for a judicial review in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lord Sandison dismissed the case on 17 February 2022 stating that there was "no general rule or principle of law that a question as to a person's sex may only properly be answered by reference to the sex stated on that person's birth certificate or GRC".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An appeal by Fair Play for Women was refused by the Inner House of the Court of Session.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has the responsibility for coordinating the census arrangements across the United Kingdom through the Office for National Statistics (ONS), which is also responsible for the census in England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 UK census was the first decennial census in the United Kingdom to include the option of completing the census documentation online.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Across the UK between 15 and 19% of census forms were submitted online.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority proposed that the 2021 census should be conducted predominantly online (with support provided for those unable to complete the census online), supplemented by the use of administrative and survey data and improve annual statistics between censuses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] For the census in 2021 the proposed target for online completion has been set to at least 65%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Research has been under way since 2011 to design a new census methodology which maximises the success of an online approach.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Issues identified also included the accuracy of administrative data sets for geographical areas below that of local authorities, problems associated with estimation and the use of address registers.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has commissioned research strands as part of a census transformation programme which was due to report by 2017 relating to the 2021 census operation, the shape of population statistics in 2021, and the shape of population statistics beyond 2021 in the lead up to 2031.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A work programme running until 2024, comprising eight phases, was developed by ONS.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Alongside this programme trials of statistics generation using administrative data were planned starting from the autumn of 2015 and running through to 2021 with the aim of ranging across the breadth, detail and accuracy of census outputs.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract for preparing, dispatching up to 16 million paper questionnaire packs (for anyone who did not want to, or could not access the census online), and then securely managing, capturing and digitising the responses was awarded to Leidos Innovations UK.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract was estimated to be worth around £65.1m.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The parent company of Leidos Innovations UK, Leidos (an American defence, aviation, information technology, and biomedical research company), merged with Lockheed Martin's IT sector in August 2016.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK was awarded the contract for the census in 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Adecco UK was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 30,000 temporary ONS workers who would be working as field staff for the 2021 census.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An advertising campaign (made under contract by M&C Saatchi) was launched under the slogan of "it's about us" at the start of 2021.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Television adverts tried to show a diverse range of people in various locations in England and Wales in front of a purple fabric screen, with a cover version of The Zombies' "This Will Be Our Year", performed by Jose McGill & The Vagaband, featuring as the advert soundtrack.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) undertakes the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The National Records of Scotland (NRS) is responsible for the census in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal was conducted on 7 October 2019 and closed for returns on 7 November 2019 in three local authority areas: parts of Glasgow City, Dumfries and Galloway and Na h-Eileanan Siar.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census was scheduled to take place on 21 March 2021, but was delayed in July 2020 by the Scottish Government because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Government has come under criticism for the way the census has been conducted, with some news outlets describing the results as being "botched" due to record low turnout rates and failing to meet the set target return rate of 94%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial turnout rates for the census in Scotland concluded with 79% return rate; an additional round of extension to filling out the census was granted to encourage returns, raising the return rate percentage to 89%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The return rate for comparison in England and Wales was 97%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] However national statistician Ian Diamond has said that despite not meeting the target, the census could still provide "really good data".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The additional round of extension cost the Scottish Government an additional £6m, and £148m in total.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Although it is a Crown Dependency and not part of the United Kingdom, Jersey carried out a census on the same day as the 2021 censuses in England and Wales, and Northern Ireland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Guernsey no longer carries out a decennial census, instead using the Rolling Electronic Census Project to produce regular census reports.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Isle of Man also undertook a full census in 2021 (having held an interim census in 2016).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results, released in June 2022, showed the recorded population of England and Wales to be 59,597,300 (56,489,800 in England and 3,107,500 in Wales), a rise of 6.3% or 3.5 million people over the previous decade.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] This was the largest population ever recorded through a census in England and Wales, and the overall population of the United Kingdom was estimated to be 67 million.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census also showed that the population of the two countries, aged 65 and over, had surpassed the number of children aged 15 and under for the first time, with 11.1 million people aged 65 and over compared with 10.4 million aged under 15.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results of the question on religion were published on 29 November 2022.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The question was voluntary but was answered by 94.0% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 46.2% of the population described themselves as "Christian", 6.5% as "Muslim", and 1.7% as "Hindu".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 37.2% of the population asserted that they had "no religion".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Wales, there were more people declaring that they had "no religion" (47%) than those affirming a Christian identity or any other religion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results on sexual orientation and gender identity questions were released on 6 January 2023.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Similarly to the religion question, this question was voluntary but was answered by 92.5% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 89.4% of the population described themselves as straight or heterosexual, 1.5% described themselves as "Gay or lesbian", 1.3% as "Bisexual" and 0.3% were described as having "[an]other sexual orientation" (with the most common being pansexual, asexual and queer).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 0.5% answered 'No' to the census question 'Is the gender you identify with the same as your sex registered at birth?' Alice Sullivan, professor of sociology at University College London, reported that in the 16 to 24 age group, 1% answered 'No' to the question.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] She said that females were more likely than males to answer 'No' in that age group, whereas in other age groups females were more likely to answer 'Yes'.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2023, when more granular data became available, Michael Biggs, professor of sociology at the University of Oxford, complained about what he perceived to be anomalies in the data on the 0.5% who identified as transgender, when disaggregated by local authority and other factors.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] He questioned whether the ONS had adequately tested the gender identity question with respondents for whom English is a second language.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for Statistics Regulation (OSR), which oversees the ONS, began an examination of Biggs' concerns about the statistics, including the reported result that 262,000 identify as transgender in England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] An anonymous government source said they believed the number 260,000 of transgender people was "hugely overstated".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In September 2024, the OSR removed official accreditation of the gender identity statistics, classifying them instead as official statistics in development.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results for Northern Ireland were published by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency in Spring 2023.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] National Records of Scotland published the first results on 14 September 2023.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The results showed that Scotland's population was 5,436,600, the highest figure on record but a slower rate of population growth, 2.7% since 2011, than the previous growth of 4.6%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The first results, in May 2024, were population estimates at output areas, as well as topical data about ethnic group, national identity, language and religion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The rest of the data was published across 2024 and into 2025.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The low response rates (88%) compared with the rest of the UK mean that the data is only partial so does not fully reflect the state of Scotland's demographics.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed there were 2,509,300 households in Scotland with at least one usual resident.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were some 930,000 single person households in Scotland and over a third of all households were single person (37.1%).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census revealed that over half a million people living in Scotland were born in the rest of the UK (563,500).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Furthermore, that a further half a million were born outside of the UK (554,900).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people born outside of the UK had increased by 185,600 since 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed the population as ageing, with over one million people aged 65 and over (1,091,000).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people under 15 was only 832,300.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] The majority of people said they had no religion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Of those who were religious in 2022, 20.4% responded ‘Church of Scotland', 13.3% ‘Roman Catholic’, 5.1% 'Other Christian' and 2.2% 'Muslim'.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] Among those who selected 'Other Christian,' 72,359 people identified as Anglican or Episcopalian.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2022 the census results showed 12.9% of people in Scotland had a minority ethnic background.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/2021-united-kingdom-census] 77.7% described themselves as 'Scottish', 9.4% as 'Other British'.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The **demography of Scotland** includes all aspects of population, past and present, in the area that is Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The population growth rate in 2011 was estimated as 0.6% per annum according to the 2011 GROS Annual Review.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Covering an area of 78,782 square kilometres (30,418 sq mi), Scotland has a population density of 67.2/km2 (174/sq mi).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Other concentrations of population include the northeast coast of Scotland, principally the regions around the cities of Aberdeen and Inverness, and the west coast around the town of Ayr.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The Scottish Highlands and the island group of Eilean Siar have the lowest population densities at 9/km2 (23/sq mi).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Glasgow has the highest population density at 3,289/km2 (8,520/sq mi).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Until April 2011, responsibility for estimating the population of Scotland, as well as recording births, deaths and marriages, was overseen by the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS), headed by the Registrar-General for Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] From 1 April 2011 onwards, the GROS merged with the National Archives of Scotland to become the National Records of Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The new organisation is still required under the terms of the Registration of Births, Deaths and Marriages (Scotland) Act 1965, to present a Registrar-General's annual report of demographic trends to the Scottish Government.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In conjunction with the rest of the United Kingdom, the National Records for Scotland is also responsible for conducting a decadal census of population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The most recent one took place in March 2022.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In the United Kingdom, a census was taken every ten years from 1801 onwards; with the exception of 1941 due to the Second World War.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The proportion of people residing in Scotland born outside the UK was 10.2% in 2022, compared with 7.0% in 2011, 3.8% in 2001 and 3.0% in 1991.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Scotland according to the 2022 census, alongside the three previous censuses.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The age distribution based on the 2011 census was as follows.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] A question on national identity was asked in the 2011 census: "what do you feel is your national identity?".
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Respondents could identify themselves as having more than one national identity.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The council areas with at least 90% of the population stating some 'Scottish' national identity were North Lanarkshire, Inverclyde, East Ayrshire and West Dunbartonshire.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The lowest proportions of people stating some 'Scottish' national identity were in Edinburgh (70%) and Aberdeen (75%).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The council areas with the highest proportions of people stating 'British' as their only national identity were Argyll and Bute and Shetland, each with 12%.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The statistics from the 2022, 2011 and 2001 censuses are set out below.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] English is by far the most commonly spoken language in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Two regional languages of Scotland, Scottish Gaelic and Modern Scots, are protected under the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Abilities in these languages for those aged three and above were recorded in the UK census 2021 as follows.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Over 170 languages are spoken in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The 4 most commonly spoken non-English languages at home (by people aged 3 and over) are: Scots (55,817), Polish (54,186), Chinese (27,381), and Urdu (23,394).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] At times during the last interglacial period (130,000–70,000 BC) Europe had a climate warmer than today's, and early humans may have made their way to what is now Scotland, though archaeologists have found no traces of this.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Glaciers then scoured their way across most of Britain, and only after the ice retreated did Scotland again become habitable, around 9600 BC.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Mesolithic hunter-gatherer encampments formed the first known settlements, and archaeologists have dated a site near Biggar to around 8500 BC.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Numerous other sites found around Scotland build up a picture of highly mobile boat-using people making tools from bone, stone and antlers, probably with a very low density of population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Neolithic farming brought permanent settlements, such as the stone house at Knap of Howar on Papa Westray dating from 3500 BC, and greater concentrations of population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Extensive analyses of Black Loch in Fife indicate that arable land spread at the expense of forest from about 2000 BC until the period of the first century AD Roman advance into lowland Scotland, suggesting an expanding settled population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Thereafter, there was re-growth of birch, oak and hazel for a period of five centuries, suggesting that the Roman invasions had a negative impact on the native population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] There are almost no written sources from which to re-construct the demography of early medieval Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Estimates have been made of a population of 10,000 inhabitants in Dál Riata and 80–100,000 for Pictland, which was probably the largest region.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] This does not include figures for parts of Northumbria now in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] It is likely that the 5th and 6th centuries saw higher mortality rates due to the appearance of bubonic plague, which may have reduced net population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The examination of burial sites for this period like that at Hallowhill, St Andrews indicate a life expectancy of only 26–29.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The known conditions have been taken to suggest it was a high fertility, high mortality society, similar to many developing countries in the modern world, with a relatively young demographic profile, and perhaps early childbearing, and large numbers of children for women.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] This would have meant that there were a relatively small proportion of available workers to the number of mouths to feed.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] This would have made it difficult to produce a surplus that would allow demographic growth and more complex societies to develop.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] From the formation of the kingdom of Alba in the tenth century, to before the Black Death reached the country in 1349, estimates based on the amount of farmable land, suggest that population may have grown from half a million to a million.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Although there is no reliable documentation on the impact of the plague, there are many anecdotal references to abandoned land in the following decades.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] If the pattern followed that in England, then the population may have fallen to as low as half a million by the end of the 15th century.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Compared with the situation after the redistribution of population in the later clearances and the industrial revolution, these numbers would have been relatively evenly spread over the kingdom, with roughly half living north of the Tay.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Perhaps ten per cent of the population lived in one of many burghs that grew up in the later medieval period, mainly in the east and south.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] It has been suggested that they would have had a mean population of about 2,000, but many would be much smaller than 1,000 and the largest, Edinburgh, probably had a population of over 10,000 by the end of the era.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Calculations based on Hearth Tax returns for 1691 indicate a population of 1,234,575, but this figure may have been seriously affected by the famines of the 1690s.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The first reliable information is a census conducted by the Reverend Alexander Webster in 1755, which shows the inhabitants of Scotland as 1,265,380.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] By the time of the first decadal census in 1801, the population was 1,608,420.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Even with the growth of industry there were insufficient good jobs, as a result, during the period 1841–1931, about 2 million Scots emigrated to North America and Australia, and another 750,000 Scots relocated to England.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] With a population of 4.8 million in 1911, Scotland sent 690,000 men to First World War, of whom 74,000 died in combat or from disease, and 150,000 were seriously wounded.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Thus, although Scots were only 10 per cent of the British population, they made up 15 per cent of the national armed forces and eventually accounted for 20 per cent of the dead.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] While emigration began to tail off in England and Wales after the First World War, it continued apace in Scotland, with 400,000 Scots, ten per cent of the population, estimated to have left the country between 1921 and 1931.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] When the Great Depression hit in the 1930s there were no easily available jobs in the US and Canada and emigration fell to less than 50,000 a year, bringing to an end the period of mass migrations that had opened in the mid-18th century.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] This contributed to the growth of the population, which reached a peak of 5,240,800 in 1974.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Thereafter it began to fall slowly, moving down to 5,062,940 in 2000.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] There was also a decrease in some urban populations as a result of policies of slum clearance, overspill and relocation to new towns, with the population of Glasgow falling from over a million in 1951 to 629,000 in 2001.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Rural areas also saw a loss of population, particularly the Highlands and Hebrides.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Scotland's population grew most years between the first census in 1855 up to around 5.2 million in 1974.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] However, from 1974 to 2000 there was a natural decrease in population, with both an excess of deaths over births and of emigration over immigration - particularly to the rest of the United Kingdom.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Since 2000 the population has increased most years and is projected to peak in 2028 at 5.48 million and thereafter decline to 5.39 million in 2045.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Both the Scottish Government and leading academics in Scotland had expressed some concern over the historic falling annual number of births in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] There were 49,863 live births registered in 2019, the lowest count since records began in 1855.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In 2004, for example, there were 4,012 more deaths than births, although for the subsequent five years this process had been reversed with 4,342 more births than deaths in 2008.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The long-term reversal in the declining birth rate of the 1990s was confirmed in 2009 when the Registrar General for Scotland reported that with 60,000 births recorded in 2008, this was the highest recorded fertility rate since 1995.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The population of children under age 5 grew by 6% (293,000) over the ten-year period between 2001 and 2011.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] However, the number of children aged 5–14 fell by 11% (69,000).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The population of people over 65 also grew by 11% (85,000) and they now represent 17% of the total population and for the first time there are more people over 65 than under 15 years of age.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Significantly, in 2011 there were 230,000 people over 80 years of age.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The 2021 United Kingdom census recorded 648,418 people who were born in Scotland but now living in England and Wales (1.1% of the total population).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The South East of England (118,021 people), North West of England (89,025) and Greater London (75,004) were the three most popular destinations, together accounting for around 43% of the Scotland-born population in England and Wales.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In the equivalent census conducted in 2022, there were 506,207 England-born and 18,219 Wales-born residents living in Scotland, for a total of 524,426 (9.6% of the total population).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Politicians and academics also noted that in the first years of the 21st century the previous trend of a net migration away from Scotland had reversed with significant immigration to Scotland from the rest of the United Kingdom.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Between 2001 and 2011 Scotland's population grew by 5% (233,000), the fastest rate of growth for at least 100 years.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Similarly, since 2004 there had also been a growing influx of arrivals from the new EU accession states such as Poland, Czech Republic, Lithuania and Latvia, contributing to the recent growth of the population.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Consequently, since 2002 the birth rate gradually increased with 53,957 births recorded in 2004, and in 2008 the number of live births was 60,041.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Between 2001 and 2022, the number of non-UK born residents living in Scotland increased from 191,571 (3.8% of the total population in Scotland) to 554,883 (10.2% of the total population).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In 2005, the Scottish Government responded to these demographic trends by introducing the Fresh Talent - Working in Scotland Scheme open to foreign (non-EU) graduates from Scotland's universities allowing them a two-year residency period after graduation.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In its 2011 review the GROS predicted that Scotland's population would rise by 10% to 5.76 million by 2035 and to 6.2m by 2085.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Until 2028 both net inward migration and the birth rate exceeding the death rate would contribute to this growth, however beyond this date population increase would be due only to a positive net migration as the ageing population would result in more deaths than births.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] This later trend would be dramatic with the number of children under 16 projected to rise by only 3% while the number of people over 65 is projected to increase by 63% (from 0.88m to 1.43m).
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In its 2022 annual population review the National Records of Scotland projected that the Scottish population would continue to rise until 2028 - peaking at 5.48 million - and would then fall by 1.8% by 2045 to 5.39 million.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] For comparison, during the latter part of the 20th century it was at its highest during the 'baby boom' of the 1960s.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The GFR reached a peak of 99.5 births per 1000 women in 1962.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In 2001 the GFR had fallen to its lowest post World War II level of 50 births per 1000 women.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] By way of historical comparison, the highest ever recorded was 53,522 in 1940.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In the 1970s there were on average between 40 and 45,000 marriages per annum.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] The lowest annual figure in recent years was 27,524 in 2009 and lowest on record was 19,655 in 1858.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] Of specific interest were the number of so-called 'tourist marriages', where neither partner was resident in Scotland.
[src:demographics-of-scotland/demographics-of-scotland] In 2011 there were 6,829 such marriages, of which 48% took place at Gretna, the most popular of all wedding venues.
